HEADWORD: Hexahemeron
<hw>Hex`a*hem"er*on</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr.
<grk>"e`x</grk> six + <?/ day; cf. L. <ets>hexa⟦eum⟧meron</ets>, Gr.
<?/.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A term of six days.</def>
<rj><au>Good.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The history of the six day's work of creation, as
contained in the first chapter of Genesis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hexamerous</ent>⟦br⟧
